#Get the accuracy scores for a model 
def getProbAccuracyScores( NAME, MODEL, X, Y ) :
    pred = MODEL.predict( X )
    probs = MODEL.predict_proba( X )
    acc_score = metrics.accuracy_score(Y, pred)
    p1 = probs[:,1]
    fpr, tpr, threshold = metrics.roc_curve( Y, p1)
    auc = metrics.auc(fpr,tpr)
    return [NAME, acc_score, fpr, tpr, auc]

#Display the ROC Curve for a model
def print_ROC_Curve( TITLE, LIST ) :
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    plt.title( TITLE )
    for theResults in LIST :
        NAME = theResults[0]
        fpr = theResults[2]
        tpr = theResults[3]
        auc = theResults[4]
        theLabel = "AUC " + NAME + ' %0.2f' % auc
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label = theLabel )
    plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0, 1])
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.show()

#print the accuracy scores 
def print_Accuracy( TITLE, LIST ) :
    print( TITLE )
    print( "======" )
    for theResults in LIST :
        NAME = theResults[0]
        ACC = theResults[1]
        print( NAME, " = ", ACC )
    print( "------\n\n" )
    
#Get the root mean squared error (RMSE) for loss amount  
def getAmtAccuracyScores( NAME, MODEL, X, Y ) :
    pred = MODEL.predict( X )
    MEAN = Y.mean()
    RMSE = math.sqrt( metrics.mean_squared_error( Y, pred))
    return [NAME, RMSE, MEAN]

def getCoefLogit( MODEL, TRAIN_DATA ) :
    varNames = list( TRAIN_DATA.columns.values )
    coef_dict = {}
    coef_dict["INTERCEPT"] = MODEL.intercept_[0]
    for coef, feat in zip(MODEL.coef_[0],varNames):
        coef_dict[feat] = coef
    print("\nCRASH")
    print("---------")
    print("Total Variables: ", len( coef_dict ) )
    for i in coef_dict :
        print( i, " = ", coef_dict[i]  )

def getCoefLinear( MODEL, TRAIN_DATA ) :
    varNames = list( TRAIN_DATA.columns.values )
    coef_dict = {}
    coef_dict["INTERCEPT"] = MODEL.intercept_
    for coef, feat in zip(MODEL.coef_,varNames):
        coef_dict[feat] = coef
    print("\nDAMAGES")
    print("---------")
    print("Total Variables: ", len( coef_dict ) )
    for i in coef_dict :
        print( i, " = ", coef_dict[i]  )

def getTreeVars( TREE, varNames ) :
   tree_ = TREE.tree_
   varName = [ varNames[i] if i != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED else "undefined!" for i in tree_.feature ]
   nameSet = set()
   for i in tree_.feature :
       if i != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED :
           nameSet.add( i )
   nameList = list( nameSet )
   parameter_list = list()
   for i in nameList :
       parameter_list.append( varNames[i] )
   return parameter_list

        continue 
    FLAG = "M_" + i 
    IMP = "IMP_" + i

    df[IMP] = df[i]
    df.loc[df[IMP].isna(), IMP] = df[i].median()
    df = df.drop(i, axis = 1)

#Remove outliers 

#First let's rebuild our list of Numbers
dt = df.dtypes
Numbers = []
for i in dt.index :
    if i in ( [ TARGET_F, TARGET_A ] ):
        continue
    #Get rid of any columns that are Boolean (only have 0/1)
    if df[i].isin([0,1]).all(): 
        continue 
    if dt[i] in (["float64","int64"]): 
        Numbers.append( i )
In [35]:
#Then replace outliers
for i in Numbers :
    #Get the mean
    theMean = df[i].mean()
    #Get the standard deviation
    theSD = df[i].std()
    #Get the maximum value 
    theMax = df[i].max()
    #Build a variable to make the cutoff be mean + 3*standard deviation
    theCutoff = round( theMean + 3*theSD )
    #Replace any number higher than theCutoff with theCutoff
    if theMax < theCutoff: 
        continue
    FLAG = "O_" + i
    TRUNC = "TRUNC_" + i
    #Creates a flag column if there was a number truncated
    df[FLAG] = (df[i] > theCutoff )+ 0
    df[TRUNC] = df[i]
    #Replace the outlier with theCutoff
    df.loc[df[TRUNC] > theCutoff, TRUNC] = theCutoff
    df = df.drop(i, axis=1)

The result of the graphviz can be see below

What we can visually take away from this decision tree is that the model is stating that a 50% debt-to-income ratio is the strongest indicator of defaulting on the loan. This actually matches what real estate agents advise spending on a mortgage: most mortgage lenders limit D:I to 45% to even recieve the inital loan. Of course this is a home equity loan which is slightly different, but the logic that the model chose is in line with convential wisdom

Now that we know that the decision tree performs well at predicting the data, let's see what columns it is choosing to predict the probability of defaulting

The root mean squared error can be thought of as the standard deviation from statistics. Basically, if our average is around 12,000 dollars for a repair, about 66 percent of the data would be between 9,000 and 15,000 if the data is normalized. Thought of another way, the RMSE shows that the error in our data is about 3,000.

Now that we have the RMSE and median, we can get a Graphviz file of this data as well.

The resulting Decision Tree can be seen below:

From the visual decision tree, we can see that the loan amount of 16,850 was the biggest driver of the amount that would be defaulted. This makes sense as a larger loan (in this case one above the 50th percentile) would be tougher to pay back, especially in tougher times. As such, the loan amount defaulted would be directly corresponding to the inital loan amount/

Random Forests¶

Thankfully we can still utilize the cleaned up data from before. The syntax for building a random forest will look very similar to decision trees since the forest is an amalgamation of 'random' trees

In [52]:
#First, we need to build the function to get the random forest variables later

def getEnsembleTreeVars( ENSTREE, varNames ) :
   importance = ENSTREE.feature_importances_
   index = np.argsort(importance)
   theList = []
   for i in index :
       imp_val = importance[i]
       if imp_val > np.average( ENSTREE.feature_importances_ ) :
           v = int( imp_val / np.max( ENSTREE.feature_importances_ ) * 100 )
           theList.append( ( varNames[i], v ) )
   theList = sorted(theList,key=itemgetter(1),reverse=True)
   return theList
